e":"1150–Deceased","1155–1191":"1155–1191","1155–Male":"1155–Deceased","1162–Male":"1162–Deceased","1164–1258":"1164–1258","1098–Male":"1098–Deceased","1062–Female":"1062–Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","1164":"1164","1098":"1098","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1062":"1062","1191":"1191","1128":"1128","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1113":"1113","1155":"1155","about 1155":"about 1155","East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland","Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Drumelzier, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Oliver Castle, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Drumelzier, Peebleshire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kylvert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: relationship name from an Old Scandinavian personal name * <i>Ketilfrøðr</i>, * <i>Ketilfrith</i>, anglicized as * <i>Cytelferð</i> which became * <i>Cylferð</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Clilverd","meanings":["English: apparently a variant of   Kilvert   with intrusive  <i>-l-</i>."]},{"name":"Kilford","meanings":["English:  see  Kilvert  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Verch Kylvert was born in Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland as the daughter of Oliver Kylvert and Kylvert. She married Udard Fraser about 1150, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1169, in Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"–1169":"–1169","1113–Male":"1113–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1128–1169":"1128–1169","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1155–1191":"1155–1191","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1164–1258":"1164–1258","1098–Male":"1098–Surnud","1062–Female":"1062–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1164":"1164","1098":"1098","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1062":"1062","1191":"1191","1128":"1128","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1113":"1113","1155":"1155","about 1155":"umbes 1155","East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland","Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Drumelzier, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Oliver Castle, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Drumelzier, Peebleshire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–1169":"–1169","1113–Male":"1113–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1128–1169":"1128–1169","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1155–1191":"1155–1191","1155–Male":"1155–Kuollut","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1164–1258":"1164–1258","1098–Male":"1098–Kuollut","1062–Female":"1062–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","1164":"1164","1098":"1098","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1062":"1062","1191":"1191","1128":"1128","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1113":"1113","1155":"1155","about 1155":"noin 1155","East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland","Drumelzier, Peeb